            When it comes to real estate investments, many taxpayers are
            surprised to find out that <strong
              >rental losses aren’t always deductible</strong
            >—even if they lost money. This is because of something called the <strong
              >Passive Activity Loss (PAL) limitation</strong
            >, a rule that often catches high-income earners off guard.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-30">Let’s break it down in simple terms.</p>
          <img src="img/blogs/2.png" class="mb-30" alt="" />
          <h4>What Is a Passive Activity?</h4>
          <p class="mb-30">
            The IRS considers most rental real estate activities to be <strong
              >passive</strong
            > by default. This means that <strong
              >you don’t materially participate</strong
            > in the day-to-day operations of the rental, even if you own and manage
            the property.
          </p>
          <h4>Under IRS rules:</h4>
          <p class="mb-30">
            Passive losses can generally <strong
              >only be deducted against passive income</strong
            > (like profits from other rentals or investments in passive businesses).
          </p>
          <p>
            If you have no passive income to offset, the loss is considered <strong
              >“suspended”</strong
            > and carried forward to future years.
          </p>

          <h4>
            The $25,000 Special Allowance (And Why It Doesn’t Always Help)
          </h4>
          <p class="mb-30">The good news? There’s an exception.</p>
          <p class="mb-30">
            If you actively participate in your rental (e.g., make management
            decisions or approve expenses), you might qualify to deduct up to <strong
              >$25,000</strong
            > of losses against <strong>non-passive income</strong> (like wages or
            business income).
          </p>
          <p class="mb-30">But here’s the catch…</p>
          <!-- Table -->
          <table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="8">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Adjusted Gross Income (AGI)</th>
                <th>How Much You Can Deduct</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>$100,000 or less</td>
                <td>Full $25,000</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>$100,000 – $150,000</td>
                <td>Partial deduction</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Over $150,000</td>
                <td>$0 deduction</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <!-- Table ends -->
          <p class="mb-30">
            If your AGI is <strong>over $150,000,</strong> the special allowance
            <strong>phases out entirely</strong>, and your rental loss becomes
            non-deductible for the year.
          </p>
          <h4>Example</h4>
          <p>Let's say:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>&#x2022;&nbsp;You and your spouse file jointly with an AGI of $231,000</li>
            <li>&#x2022;&nbsp;You had a rental property loss of $8,000</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mb-30">Because your AGI is over $150,000, you don’t qualify for the $25,000 allowance. The entire $8,000 loss is <strong>suspended</strong> and carried forward. It won’t reduce your taxable income this year.</p>

          <h4>What Happens to the Suspended Loss?</h4>
          <p>Don’t worry—your loss isn’t gone forever.</p>
          <p>You can claim the suspended losses in future years:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>1. When your income drops below the phase-out range</li>
            <li>2. When you generate passive income to offset it</li>
            <li>3. When you sell the rental property in a fully taxable sale</li>
          </ol>
          <h4>Is There a Way to Avoid This?</h4>
          <p>Yes, in some cases:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>&#x2022;&nbsp;<strong>Qualify as a Real Estate Professional (RE Pro Status)</strong></li>
            <li>&#x2022;&nbsp;<strong>Group rentals as part of a business activity </strong>you materially participate in</li>
            <li>&#x2022;&nbsp;<strong>Sell the property </strong>and unlock all suspended losses</li>
            <li>&#x2022;&nbsp;Offset with <strong>other passive income</strong></li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mb-30">
            But these strategies require careful planning and may not apply to everyone.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-30">
            If you’re not seeing your rental losses reflected on your tax return, <strong>you’re not alone</strong>. Passive Activity Loss rules are one of the most misunderstood areas in personal taxes.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-30">
            Understanding how and when you can deduct these losses—and planning accordingly—can help you make smarter tax decisions moving forward.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-30">
            Got rental properties and unsure about your losses? Let's connect and review your return together. I’ll help you understand what’s allowed, what’s not, and how to make the most of your real estate investments.
          </p>
